comments.body:
[~sjones] I misplaced the link where I found information about the below policy's construction, but given that structure, I think we can verify the principal and condition. Do we already have condition handling code that can understand the condition variable? That "aud" is audience which is clientID. I assume the service would:
 a) look for the federated principal and use that to lookup the oidc provider (or verify it's the one already loaded).
 b) look for the condition variable prefixed by the federated principal (auth.globus.org in this case), and support predefined variables after the colon (aud in this case). If aud matches one of the clientIDs in the oidc provider, this check passes
 c) some policies can have other conditions (I'll look for that doc again). We may need to support those as well.
If the above steps pass, we proceed with account lookup and token generation.

{code}
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Id": "RoleForLoginWithGlobus",
  "Statement": {
    "Effect": "Allow",
    "Principal": {"Federated": "auth.globus.org"},
    "Action": "sts:AssumeRoleWithWebIdentity",
    "Condition": {
      "StringEquals": {"auth.globus.org:aud": "659067ec-9698-44a8-88ea-db31e071447a"}
    }
  }
}
{code}

From a comment on another issue, but I think most relevant to this story:

{quote}
The AssumeRoleWithWebIdentity call requires at least 2 https requests. Is there any value in caching results from openid-configuration or jwks.json fetches? What about the ssl cert thumbprint?
{quote}

My preference would be to create another story covering caching. Caching is important, but is not essential for "tracer" level functionality. My initial thoughts are that we would need to cache both for performance reasons and (possibly) to have a persistent? cache to allow for short outages of providers.
